@MParris' Beckhoff recommendation is sound.  One of the issues with power monitoring is that it can require A LOT of analog inputs.  Most IO gateway products on the market severely lack analog inputs.  And, with PLCs, analog input cards can be quite costly.  Beckhoff is a good solution because the backplane modules are universal across their portfolio and there are few limitations in their use.  This allows one to build a "dense" gateway full of analog inputs or power monitoring modules.  This is preferable to buying more gateways based on the inputs that are available.  Also, using an IoT "bus coupler" instead of a processor designed for machine control can help reduce cost.

Another solution is to use IO-Link.  IFM offers an analog input modules, DP2200 and DP1222, that can be connected to an IO-Link Master.  These can be quite economical relative to traditional analog input cards.  These input modules can be connected to widely-available analog current/voltage sensors.  By converting the analog signal to IO-Link, it provides quite a bit of flexibility.  IO-Link works over unshielded M12 cables.  This reduces the amount of interference and shielded cables.  It allows the gateway (aka IO-Link Master) to be located further away from the sensors.  This can be particularly useful for monitoring dispersed power infrastructure (e.g., switch gear, bus bar) or brownfield assets where 24VDC or PoE may not be present.

IFM's IO-Link Masters have MQTT and various fieldbus interfaces.  For MQTT, data comes in as basic JSON payloads.  This will likely require the use of some form of "DataOps" to build structure and context (e.g., three phase, units of measure, asset, area).  While it may sound like nuisance to introduce a PLC and fieldbus into this, IFM maintains a really nice set of programming libraries (e.g., Function Block, AOI) to decode the IO-Link payloads.  Using a central PLC as gateway to decode IO-Link and build context could be an option as well.

All of them run at the edge.  You can also run instances in the cloud if you'd like, and there's a multi-hub option.  

